<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE MUSICAL INSIGHT OF PEOPLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In re People magazine's "de facto ban" on articles about rap music, as reported 
in the May 13 Pop Eye column: 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps the lack of interest in rap articles is due in part to the fact that 
90% of rap records have identical machine-generated robot rhythms, identical 
percussive sounds, identical female shrieks, identical topics and identical 
beats-per-minute. 
</P>
<P>
And when it comes to the only genuine (non-synthesized) sound -- the rapper 
himself -- we get the same inflections, the same cadence, the same number of 
words and syllables per line. 
</P>
<P>
In short, this is a very, very tired musical style, so if it's so boring to 
listen to, who wants to read about it? 
</P>
<P>
ELON JOHNSON 
</P>
<P>
Compton 
</P>
</TEXT>
