<HEADLINE>
<P>
'GURU' EDUCATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I read with interest "The Gurus" by Russ Wiles (May 6) concerning the role 
consultants play in assisting residential developers in their most critical 
decisions on where, when and what to build. 
</P>
<P>
Wiles correctly noted "there are no qualifying exams or required educational 
prerequisites to enter the consulting field." 
</P>
<P>
This is true, but your readers might like to know that the American Society of 
Real Estate Counselors, founded 37 years ago and a professional affiliate of 
the National Assn. of Realtors, is dedicated to enhancing the quality of advice 
available to the public on property matters. 
</P>
<P>
Membership in the society and the CRE (Counselor of Real Estate) designation is 
awarded only after an extensive evaluation of a real estate counselor by his 
peers. It recognizes than an individual has demonstrated judgment, integrity 
and experience in real estate counseling matters and client service. Obtaining 
the services of a CRE assures the user of securing unbiased, 
non-contingent-based advice. 
</P>
<P>
Your readers may contact the society at 430 N. Michigan Ave., Chicago, Ill. 
60611, or calling (312) 329-8427. 
</P>
<P>
EUGENE P. CARVER 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
