<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 7; Column 5; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
709 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN RIGHT; 
</P>
<P>
NO ONE KNOWS WHAT WILL HAPPEN NEXT; 
</P>
<P>
LET'S WEIGH THE URGE FOR ARMS DEALS AGAINST HISTORY'S LESSON -- THE UNFORESEEN 
DOES THE MOST DAMAGE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANE KIRKPATRICK, Jeane Kirkpatrick writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Is the Cold War over? Not if Mikhail Gorbachev and his colleagues are having 
second thoughts about withdrawing Soviet troops from Europe. 
</P>
<P>
Is the world becoming safer? Not if the United States accepts constraints on 
advanced weapons while dangerous Soviet intercontinental ballistic weapons 
remain unrestricted. 
</P>
<P>
Has democracy triumphed? Not yet. Not in the Soviet Union or China or almost 
anywhere in Asia outside of Japan. Not in the Middle East or Africa. While 
democracy spreads in Latin America, fundamentalism spreads in Muslim nations. 
</P>
<P>
Reason has not yet replaced force in Kashmir or Lebanon, Gaza, Iraq or 
Lithuania. 
</P>
<P>
George Bush cannot write enough notes to comfort all the families of all the 
victims of violence -- in Nepal, Malaysia, Afghanistan, Jordan, Beirut and 
Nazareth. Secretary of State James A. Baker III cannot cut enough deals to 
eliminate all the proliferating weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
<P>
It is not true that the case for democracy has vanquished all opposing 
philosophies, only that it has vanquished European Marxism. We have not arrived 
at the Heavenly City of 18th-Century philosophers or the Crystal Palace of 
19th-Century prophets. 
</P>
<P>
The fact is that no one knows what will happen next. The great movements of the 
20th Century have come as a surprise. Communism, fascism, Nazism, Islamic 
fundamentalism -- each was an unexpected development. Each seemed unlikely even 
as it fastened a fanatical grip on an unwary society. Lenin and his Bolsheviks 
were as implausible a band of conspirators as ever moved into a volatile 
political situation. They were as implausible as Hitler and the freakish 
freebooters who met with him in Bavaria and Berlin, as implausible as the 
Ayatollah Khomeini and his frenzied followers, as implausible as the Chinese 
Red Guard or Pol Pot's baby-faced killers in Cambodia. 
</P>
<P>
Ours is a century of violent revolutions, each more unexpected than the last. 
It is a century of utopian dreams and megalomaniacal revolutionaries who, as 
rulers, move their subjects about like so many pawns on a gigantic chessboard 
-- into cities, out of cities; from re-education onto farms, from farms into 
re-education. 
</P>
<P>
Always the world is surprised. We are surprised by war and surprised by peace; 
surprised by economic growth (as in the Asian miracle) and surprised by 
economic failure (as under socialism). We were surprised by Stalin's ruthless 
conquests and by Gorbachev's abandonment of those conquests. 
</P>
<P>
The truth is that we have not discerned the "laws" of historical development, 
probably because there are none. Individual leaders have a greater impact on 
history than we prefer to think because individuals are so unpredictable. 
</P>
<P>
Much of what has happened since World War II has come as a surprise. And much 
that lies ahead will also surprise us. We did not foresee the resurgence of 
German and Japanese economic power, nor do we know the consequences for them or 
us of Japan's highly leveraged security market and wide-ranging acquisitions. 
No one anticipated the rapid liquidation of the Soviet Union's European empire. 
Nor did we foresee the Soviet government's sudden halt of its withdrawal from 
Eastern Europe. We do not know how long Gorbachev will retain power or what his 
policies will be while he remains. 
</P>
<P>
We are more involved with one another than ever, but that does not mean that we 
like each other better. Some Japanese dream of saying "no" to America. Some 
French will not say "yes" to NATO or to a special role for the United States in 
Europe. The size and shape of the European community are less certain than 
Brussels pretends. Difficulties in breaking East Germany out of the Warsaw Pact 
expand that unknown. Uncertainty hangs as heavy as London fog over the future, 
obscuring it. 
</P>
<P>
It is a good time now, in advance of the American-Soviet summit, for the U.S. 
government to step back and think again about a sweeping arms deal that does 
not affect the presence of Soviet troops and tanks in Europe or the continued 
production of ICBMs with a well-understood first-strike capability. 
</P>
<P>
It is time for the Bush Administration to reiterate Ronald Reagan's message at 
Reykjavik: A deal? Yes, but not at the price of enhanced American vulnerability 
in a still very uncertain world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052790-0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 224952 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 27, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 7; Column 1; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
754 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN LEFT; 
</P>
<P>
THE MAJORITY RULES, BUT NOT FOR LONG; 
</P>
<P>
CALIFORNIA'S VOTING POPULATION IS 80% WHITE; THE URBAN SCHOOLS' IS 20%. A 'NEW 
POLITICS' IS DAWNING. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICHARD REEVES, Richard Reeves is a Washington-based columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There will be an election next week in a state called California, a pleasant 
and orderly nation of white people living well in Mediterranean climates along 
the Pacific Ocean between Oregon and Mexico. The big contest is between Atty. 
Gen. John Van de Kamp and former San Francisco Mayor Dianne Feinstein for the 
Democratic nomination for governor. 
</P>
<P>
The winner will face Republican Sen. Pete Wilson in November for the chance to 
govern a place called California, an unruly and rather wary conglomeration of 
people of many colors, many incomes, many cultures. 
</P>
<P>
There are two Californias sharing the same space these days, in different 
decades, different time zones. There is a 20-year gap, at least, between 
California on election days and California on any other day of the year. Next 
Tuesday, more than 80% of the voters will be white. Next Wednesday, almost half 
of California will be black and many shades of brown and tan. 
</P>
<P>
The current coexistence of old and new Californias is one of the most 
extraordinary episodes of change in American history -- and most American 
history is about change. The voting population of California in the 1980s was, 
and will be on June 5, between 80% and 85% white -- and 7% black, 7% Latino and 
2% or 3% Asian. But the overall population is now estimated at only 58% white 
-- or Anglo, as most say here. "Euro-American" is used by some scholars in 
anticipation of the day, not far away, when Anglos are again a minority here, 
as they were until the 19th Century. 
</P>
<P>
The overall population, as opposed to the voting citizenry, includes both 
children and non-citizens, including immigrants, some legal, some not. But if 
you used demographic statistics including only actual U.S. citizens above the 
voting age of 18, the white total would still reach only a little more than 
60%. 
</P>
<P>
"There are new and potentially dangerous pressures in the demographic gaps 
now," said Mervyn Field, director of the California Poll, which produced some 
of the figures used here. "The non-voters are becoming more and more different 
from voters in color, class and life-style." 
</P>
<P>
The time and place to see that is any Sunday at the intersection of Alvarado 
and 7th streets near downtown Los Angeles. If you are white and middle-aged, as 
I am, you can sit in Langer's delicatessen with a collection of urban types as 
American as bagels and lox -- a cross-section of the people who vote in Los 
Angeles and most other American cities, Jewish and Christian, most white but a 
couple of blacks. 
</P>
<P>
Step outside and you magically transcend great distance and time. You are in 
Guatemala City. The streets are crowded with families, all Latino, speaking 
Spanish in the accents of Guatemala, Mexico, El Salvador, Nicaragua and 
Honduras. Men wait in long lines to buy ices or to make telephone calls. 
Children chase each other through a maze of food stalls along the edge of 
Westlake Park. There is nothing visible to indicate that this is the United 
States until three Los Angeles Fire Department trucks come screaming down 
Alvarado as if they were spaceships from another planet. How many people on the 
streets are legally in this country? Maybe half, but the ones who have American 
citizenship don't often vote -- and neither do the Asians, mostly legal, in 
other parts of the state. 
</P>
<P>
If Langer's customers reflect today's voting, Alvarado, Koreatown and Asian 
neighborhoods up and down the coast reflect tomorrow's California. More than 
80% of the children in the lower grades of Los Angeles schools are "people of 
color." Only 33% of the students are white at Berkeley, the best of the fine 
schools that make up the University of California system. Ten years ago, the 
proportion of whites at Berkeley was 58%, but their numbers have eroded with 
affirmative action and the scholastic achievements of Asians and 
Asian-Americans. 
</P>
<P>
The schools, from kindergarten to college, are where the races and cultures of 
modern California come together -- and divide. White resentment over admission 
to the state university is balanced by minority-group resentment about the 
flight of white students from public schools, usually followed by the 
reluctance of voters and politicians to pay or levy taxes to maintain the kind 
of high-quality California schools represented by the Norman Rockwell past. 
</P>
<P>
So next Tuesday, white voters will choose Van de Kamp or Feinstein to oppose 
Wilson. But the victory photos will look like old tintypes the moment they are 
developed. This is already the politics of the past in the California. 
</P>
</TEXT>
