<HEADLINE>
<P>
NONFICTION IN BRIEF: ETHNIC L.A. BY ZENA PEARLSTONE (HILLCREST PRESS, P.O. BOX 
10636, BEVERLY HILLS, CALIF. 90210: $12.95; 188 PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Sonja Bolle 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles is the second-largest Mexican, Armenian, Korean, Filipino, 
Salvadoran and Guatemalan city in the world, and more than 50 foreign-language 
newspapers are published in L.A. County, says Zena Pearlstone in "Ethnic L.A." 
Her book describes the enormous human diversity of the city, to which the 
author applies the metaphor mosaic rather than melting pot, because the 
communities tend to retain their individual characters. With its statistics and 
local histories of the various ethnic groups, this book can be used as a 
reference, or it can function as a guidebook: It concludes with lists of ethnic 
foods, religious centers and a calendar of celebrations that could keep any 
tourist occupied every day of the year. Sonja Bolle 
</P>
</TEXT>
