<HEADLINE>
<P>
NONFICTION IN BRIEF: THE AMERICAN CIRCUS AN ILLUSTRATED HISTORY BY JOHN CULHANE 
(HENRY HOLT: $39.95; 504 PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Sam Hall Kaplan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Before television, amusement parks, country fairs, public zoos and 
entertainment zones, there was the circus. In the United States, ever since 
1785 when in Philadelphia a Thomas Pool presented "Feats of Horsemanship . . . 
and a Clown to Amuse the Spectators," the circus has enthralled ladies and 
gentlemen and children of all ages with increasingly spectacular acts and 
abiding dedication, under makeshift tents, in sports arenas and in open fields. 
</P>
<P>
Author and sometime performing clown John Culhane notes in his three-ring 
effort of a book that the history of the circus has been rich and rocky, marked 
by storybook characters and magical moments, personal tragedies and public 
disasters. It has been, in effect, a theatrical high-wire act, teetering 
between failure and acclaim, and Culhane in his obvious enthusiasm tries to 
tell it all. 
</P>
<P>
Culhane's narrative begins with pioneer Pool's performances and moves through 
the turbulent era of P. T. Barnum, his competition with Bailey, their merger, 
the rise of the Ringling brothers, their merger with Barnum and Bailey in 1919 
to create the halcyon days of the super circus, to the present diverse efforts. 
The institutional history is interspersed with the legends of Buffalo Bill and 
Annie Oakley, animal trainer Clyde Beatty, the acrobatic Great Wallendas, clown 
Emmett Kelly, Gunther Gebel Williams and his cage of mixed cats, and dozens of 
other lesser characters who have performed under the Big Top. 
</P>
<P>
The total is an evocative, somewhat overflowing, starry-eyed history of a 
grand, if wavering, tradition. Culhane's effort reads not unlike the feat of 
immortal clown and contortionist Lou Jacobs, who orchestrated the packing of a 
midget car with a gaggle of clowns. And while the illustrations could have been 
of better quality and the design more imaginative (as would befit the book's 
subject and price), "The American Circus" as a history of an endearing 
theatrical tradition deserves the center ring.Sam Hall Kaplan 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The consummate showman and self-promoter, Phineas Taylor (better known 
as P. T.) Barnum, whose name is practically synonymous with circus, from "The 
American Circus: An Illustrated History" (see review this page). 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
