<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BUZZ: TODAY'S NEWS, TOMORROW'S TELEVISION; 
</P>
<P>
LOOK! UP IN THE SKY, IT'S SUPER DAVE! AND SIMPSONS DOLLS! AND THE CHECKOUT 
CHANNEL? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Daniel Cerone, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SERIES 
</P>
<P>
Television personality Bob Hilton has been named to host NBC's revival of the 
game show "Let's Make a Deal," which joins NBC's daytime lineup July 9. Hilton 
has announced such shows as "Win, Lose or Draw," "The Dating Game," "Jokers 
Wild," "The Newlywed Game," "Card Sharks" and "Tic Tac Dough." 
</P>
<P>
"Memories. . .Then and Now," a half-hour weekly nostalgia series produced by 
NBC News Productions, is scheduled to make its national syndicated debut Sept. 
15 in more than 60% of the country-including KNBC in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
"Captain Planet and the Planeteers," TBS' new animated environmental series, is 
set to debut this fall in more than 100 syndicated markets, including KTTV in 
Los Angeles. The series, featuring a gaggle of celebrity voices, including Tom 
Cruise, focuses on a superhero and his five international Planeteers who battle 
environmental villains out to destroy the Earth. 
</P>
<P>
Writer-producer Bob Einstein will reprise his role as Super Dave Osborne for 25 
new episodes of "Super Dave," Showtime's comedy-variety series about a 
daredevil stuntman's tireless attempts at unsuccessful stunts. The new 
installments, now shooting in Los Angeles and Toronto, will debut later this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
MINISERIES 
</P>
<P>
Linda Lavin will executive produce "The Sunset Gang," a three-part "American 
Playhouse" miniseries about a group of old folks living in a Florida retirement 
community. The production, based on a short story collection by Warren Adler, 
who wrote the book "The War of the Roses," will air in October. 
</P>
<P>
MOVIES 
</P>
<P>
Jill Eikenberry, already distressed by an emotional breakdown, is kidnaped by 
Michael Tucker in "Archie's Wife," a CBS movie shooting in Denver for future 
broadcast. Tucker, an incompetent bank robber on the run from the law and two 
slimy loan sharks, drags Eikenberry from one hiding place to the next-including 
the home of his ex-wife (Elaine Stritch). 
</P>
<P>
Production has been completed on "Babies," a lighthearted NBC drama starring 
Lindsay Wagner, Dinah Manoff and Marcy Walker as three women whose biological 
time clocks are ticking out of control. The movie is scheduled for telecast in 
the 1990-91 season. 
</P>
<P>
Michael York, Alison Doody, Ben Taylor, Geraldine Chaplin and Billie Whitelaw 
will star in the TNT movie "Duel of Love," a romantic adventure based on 
Barbara Cartland's novel. The story follows Doody, a high-spirited London 
debutante in 1821, whose evil cousin, played by York, is bent on killing the 
man she loves. The movie, now shooting in London, will air later this year. 
</P>
<P>
SPECIALS 
</P>
<P>
Florence Henderson has been signed to host the sixth annual "Mrs. World 
Pageant," a two-hour syndicated television special taping Aug. 11 at Hong 
Kong's Academy of Performing Arts. Current Mrs. World, Lucila Boggiano of Peru, 
will crown the winner of the pageant. Henderson has hosted the showhowr the 
past three years. 
</P>
<P>
NEW CHANNELS 
</P>
<P>
TBS and ActMedia, an in-store marketing company, have announced the launch of 
Checkout Channel, a national television network that will satellite-deliver 
live programming to supermarkets across the country. Beginninggearly next year, 
Checkout Channel will place televisions at checkout lines in more than 5,000 
markets, featuring news, weather, sports, business and consumer information 
programming from TBSU cable news networks, CNN and Headline News. 
</P>
<P>
LICENSING AGREEMENTS 
</P>
<P>
America's favorite animated family, "The Simpsons," will step into consumers' 
homes in three-dimensional form this fall thanks to an exclusive toy licensing 
agreement announced by Mattel Toys and Twentieth Century Fox. The worldwide 
agreement calls for Simpsons action figures, vehicles, play sets, dolls, 
preschool products and child-size accessories. 
</P>
<P>
Players International has signed an exclusive licensing agreement to produce 
"Jeopardy!S and "Wheel of Fortune" telephone games beginning next month in 
select markets. By dialing a 900 number, callers can participate in telephone 
versions of the popular TV game shows at a cost of $1 to $2 per minute. A 
minimum of $100,000 in cash and prizes will be awarded each month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Real-life husband and wife and "L.A. Law" husband and wife Michael 
Tucker and Jill Eikenberry are in Denver filming "Archie's Wife," a CBS movie. 
; Drawing, Come fall, Mattel will have dolls and action figures of Bart and the 
rest of "The Simpsons." 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
