<HEADLINE>
<P>
FRESNO; 
</P>
<P>
U.S. ACCUSES 12 OF SMUGGLING POT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal grand jury has indicted 12 people, accusing them of being members of 
a Tulare County-based marijuana smuggling ring that has been operating for more 
than a year. The indictments charged the 12 with 22 counts each of conspiracy 
and smuggling marijuana. U.S. Atty. 
</P>
<P>
David Levi said members of the alleged ring, which operated in three states, 
brought more than 1,000 pounds of marijuana into the United States from Mexico 
in 11 trips between January, 1989, and Dec. 31, 1989, by concealing it in 
secret compartments built into motor homes. He said the marijuana was smuggled 
across the border crossings in Texas, Arizona and California. Levi said Amador 
Barragan, 35, and Alberto Barragan, 32, both of Porterville, were the leaders 
of the smuggling ring. All suspects are in custody, Levi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
